Local engagement as a countermeasure against populism
PARIS – The parties that once dominated Western democracies have been shaken at their core.
Many – including in France, Italy, Greece, and the United Kingdom – have suffered crushing electoral defeats.
Others have changed so dramatically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of the former president Ronald Reagan.
These developments are happening everywhere in the West.
The leaderships of the once dominant parties oscillate between denial and despair while populists fish for their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to acknowledge a legitimate reason for their defeat and label their supporters as "pitiful," as Hillary Clinton did just before she lost to Trump in 2016; others are too frightened by the populist wave to launch a counteroffensive.
But neither denial nor self-satisfaction will dissolve the entrenched political situation.
The progressives must reposition themselves, and this begins with diagnosing the shortcomings of traditional parties.
A part of the problem is that the traditional parties have not recognized the true issues of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlefields, they ignored declining social mobility, intensifying environmental crises, increasing geographic inequality, tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other topics that actually matter to voters.
Decades ago, they were the vanguards.
Today, they stand alone in the forest, wondering where everyone has gone.
The social sciences might have an answer as to why the mainstream has veered off course.
The gap between their objective analysis of reality and government policy has widened into a chasm.
In most Western countries, economists have long been aware of the increasing disparity in income and other indicators between some wealthy, globalization-benefiting cities and the rest of the country.
But until French President Emmanuel Macron's government did it, no national head of government had implemented tax cuts based on place of residence.
As a result of this policy, now 1% of French GDP is primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
Traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters instead of only through the filters of media and opinion polls.
In 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! launched the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What voters told the respondents became the basis for Macron's presidential campaign.
For example, "The Great March" had collected countless statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual misconduct against women, and Macron promised to address the issue if he were elected.
At the time, Macron's stance made him the target of his opponents' jokes; however, their laughter quickly faded with the rise of the #MeToo era.
A precise understanding of society alone is not enough.
The traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
They have long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, where activists distribute flyers at intervals and cheer on the candidates.
This was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that views democracy as a marketplace consisting of state providers (the government) and consumers (citizens).
According to this view, the sole purpose of a party is to seize and maintain power.
It is no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological edge over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups that could mobilize people for elections, organize protests, and launch petitions.
But this model no longer works.
Citizens today refuse to be mere consumers of state policy.
Along with higher education levels, new demands for participation emerged.
Voters want to be treated as political actors with rights, not as pawns in someone else's game.
Moreover, governments are no longer the sole providers of political measures.
This is one of the harsh lessons we learned during the two years we worked alongside Macron at the Élysée Palace.
Today's most important political challenges – climate change, religious extremism, digital disruptions, and gender equality – cannot be solved solely by national governments.
These challenges require deep cultural changes and, in most cases, measures on sub- and supra-national levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the barriers to political participation, so traditional parties can no longer rely on the gatekeeper advantage and entrenched support networks.
Those who can handle Google, Twitter, and Facebook well do not need an ancient party apparatus.
Political movements need to be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete actions, not just elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative "back office"; the front office should be staffed with people on the ground.
At La République En Marche!, we refer to this as local citizen projects.
These can range from after-school reading courses and integration programs for immigrants to community gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, it is about offering tailored solutions to local problems and thus strengthening communities.
Such projects should be considered essential complements to state policy today.
In the future, the ability of a party to offer rewarding pathways for political and community engagement will be crucial to its attractiveness.
And by demonstrating their reform policy daily "live," the parties have already prepared the ground for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what needs to be said, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the hard lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win over the people.
Reestablishing the connection to the concerns of voters thus goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need a progressive politics on the ground.
